Sorry, I couldn't find anything but the site written in Japanese.
According to the following site, the 俺に here can be replaced with 俺が.
>俺にしてあげられることがあるなら = 俺がしてあげられることがあるなら
>If there's anything I can do for you

>Why is 俺にして here instead of 俺は?
It's not にして but に (particle) + して(the te form of する)
I guess に is used in place of が to avoid the repetition of the same particle.

>能力の主体「に」
>能力の主体とは、能力や知覚状態の持ち主のこと。
>「できる」「可能形(可能動詞)」などの能力を表す動詞、「見える」「聞こえる」「わかる」などの知覚状態を表す動詞の主体
>能力の主体は「が」で表すこともできる
>https://www.hamasensei.com/grammar5/#toc47

Considering just doing the Reschenpass. The Bernina is a massive detour. Would save me an entire day.

>That cave has a lot of iron - Tá a lán iarainn sa uaimh sin

>There's a village over there
I can only approach this in an SG framework, here's my crack
Tha baile ann thall
even then, im not sure im right so take what you will from that sentence and irishise it, but i reckon one of the vague demonstratives should be used for "over there" and the existential ann, which i think is what differs SG from Irish a bit.
>My house is made out of oak planks - Mo theach tógta as phleancanna darach
You need Tá, I would use the periphrastic way, so an teach agam instead of mo theach and i would use the preposition "le" - with, instead of "as" - out of, when translating this. so my house is made with oak planks rather than out of. but im no native so take my advice with salt.
